{"id":"ebl-1503512011321-1503512011325-0","version":"","unitCode":"NAA","linkedId":"","type":"ead_collection","content":{"freetext":{"identifier":[{"label":"Identifier","content":"NAA.PhotoLot.R81A"}],"creator":[{"label":"Creator","content":"Hegemann, Elizabeth Compton, 1897-1962"}],"originalsloc":[{"label":"Existence and Location of Originals note","content":"Originals in the Huntington Library (photCL 125)."}],"bioghist":[{"label":"Biographical/Historical note","content":"Elizabeth Compton Hegemann (1897-1962) was born near Cincinatti, Ohio, though she spent many of her summers visiting her grandparents in Southern California. She married her first husband, Mike Harrison, in 1925 and moved with him to the South Rim of the Grand Canyon, where he worked for the National Park Service. They developed strong relationships with the Navajo, Hopi, and Havasupai Indians in that region. Hegemann separated from Harrison in 1928 and moved to Tuba City. She married Harry Rorick in 1929 and the two co-owned the Shonto Trading Post near Tsegi Canyon on the Navajo Reservation from 1929-1938."}],"unitdate":[{"flag":["era:ce","normal:1917/1934","type:inclusive"],"label":"Date","indexedContent":"1917/1934","content":"circa 1922-1934"}],"custodhist":[{"label":"Custodial History note","content":"Donated by Elizabeth Compton Hegemann, circa 1962."}],"index":[{"label":"Addl. KW Subj","content":"Navaho"}],"physdesc":[{"label":"Extent","content":"396 Copy negatives (acetate, 35mm)"}],"odd":[{"label":"Local Call Number(s)","content":"NAA Photo Lot R81A"},{"label":"Reproduction Note","content":"Copy negatives made by Elizabeth Compton Hegemann."}],"accessrestrict":[{"label":"Restrictions","content":"The collection is open for research.\n\nAccess to the collection requires an appointment."}],"objectType":[{"label":"Type","indexedContent":"Collection descriptions","content":"Collection descriptions"},{"label":"Type","indexedContent":"Archival materials","content":"Archival materials"},{"label":"Type","indexedContent":"Copy negatives","content":"Copy negatives"},{"label":"Type","indexedContent":"Photographs","content":"Photographs"},{"label":"Type","indexedContent":"Negatives","content":"Negatives"}],"scopecontent":[{"label":"Scope and Contents note","content":"Photographs made during Elizabeth Compton Hegemann\u0027s trips to Hopi and Navajo reservations in the 1920s and early 1930s. They include images of Navajo, Hopi, and some Havasupai Indians, as well as the Grand Canyon and trading posts. Her photographs relating to Southwest Indians depict agriculture, crafts, and ceremonies, including a Navaho Squaw Dance and Hopi Niman Kachina ceremonies. There are also some images of Charles F. Lummis, Earl Halstead Morris, and John Wetherill."}],"genre_format":[{"label":"Genre/Form","indexedContent":"Photographs","content":"Photographs"},{"label":"Genre/Form","indexedContent":"Negatives","content":"Negatives"}],"bibliography":[{"label":"Bibliography","content":"Photographs published in Elizabeth Compton Hegemann, Navaho Trading Days, Albuquerque : University of New Mexico Press, 1963."}],"culture":[{"label":"Culture","indexedContent":"Hopi Pueblo","content":"Hopi Pueblo"},{"label":"Culture","indexedContent":"Diné (Navajo)","content":"Diné (Navajo)"},{"label":"Culture","indexedContent":"Havasupai (Coconino)","content":"Havasupai (Coconino)"},{"label":"Culture","indexedContent":"Indians of North America","content":"Indians of North America -- Southwest, New"}],"userestrict":[{"label":"Rights","content":"This copy collection has been obtained for reference purposes only. He likely first developed and presented it for a previous occasion at Emory since the file is dated May 2007. The file \"EMEA board presentation.wpd\" is from the same Cape Town conference. Karp gave a presentation to Emory\u0027s international advisory board (Europe, Middle East, Africa). The file \"Skidmore Conference Notes.wpd\" were for a presentation he gave during a visit around the opening of the Tang Museum at Skidmore called \"Transformation in the College Museum.\" Some of the material in the presentation draws on other papers. The file \"Chicago Conference.doc\" contains the notes that Karp used for his last conference presentation, which was in June 2011 in Chicago. Kratz developed these notes and a\ntranscription of Karp\u0027s presentation into the paper \"Collecting, Exhibiting, and Interpreting: Museums as Midwives and Mediators of Meaning,\" published in Museum Anthropology in 2014 as part of a special issue of papers from the symposium\n\"Collecting Contemporary Urban Materials for the Museum Visitor of the 22nd Century.\" See also files in the folder \"Project and paper notes\" which relate to projects Karp was thinking about and working on in his last several years. Born in Baltimore, Maryland, Dorsey was ordained by the Protestant Episcopal Church in 1871 and began missionary work among the Ponca Tribe shortly thereafter.  Though he was quick to learn the Ponca language, illness forced him to abandon his work in 1873.  He returned to Baltimore and became a staff member of the BAE after its establishment in 1879.  With the BAE, he completed studies on the Omaha, Osage, Kansa, and Dakota Tribes, as well as on Athapascan, Kusan, Takilman, and Yakonan languages in Oregon."}],"unitdate":[{"flag":["era:ce","type:inclusive"],"label":"Date","indexedContent":"","content":"circa 1890"}],"relatedmaterial":[{"label":"Location of Other Archival Materials","content":"The National Anthropological Archives holds the James O.
